<font color="#FF0000">WHAT IS &quot;DIALOG?&quot;</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov  6  2:29:37 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
A few thoughts &quot;blowing in the wind.&quot;  <br><br>
--I have stood up and told Cookie that I did not like some of the language he used.  I thought it racist in its context, told him so, and we hashed it out months ago.<br><br>
--I have done the same with the poster above, who as I recall had a hard time with Vietnamese immigrants.  We thought we came to some conclusions after that dialog.<br><br>
I am through hashing this stuff out endlessly.  This site is for &quot;dialog,&quot; not name-calling. A &quot;dialog&quot; is a conversation (Standard College Dictionary, 1963).  We can converse on anything we wish, using any language we wish, as long as we show respect for one another.  There has been precious little respect shown here for the Vietnam Veterans by one particular poster.<br><br>
In 'Nam, the term &quot;Doc&quot; or &quot;Doctor&quot; was given only to people who earned our respect.  There were medical personal there with an &quot;MD&quot; or &quot;Ph.D&quot; attached to their names who would not gain the term, &quot;Doc&quot; until they had earned it.  We had to trust their judgement.  Without that trust, we really did not care what their rank, or what their particular title was.  But others, such as &quot;Doc&quot; Del, who did not have the degrees or MD behind their name were called &quot;Doc&quot; because they earned the title, many times under very harsh, combat conditions by putting their butts on the line and saving lives.  <br><br>
Until trust is re-established, a dialog cannot occur; what we will end up with is a rock-throwing contest, and nobody throws better than Vietnam Vets when they choose to do so.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


